export const story = {"seriesId":"downriver","storyId":"downriver","storyKey":"downriver/downriver","seriesTitle":"Downriver","seriesDescription":"Samuel Corwin is eleven years old when he joins his uncle on a timber raft floating six hundred miles down the Mississippi River. It is 1854, and the raft moves only by the strength of twenty men pulling at the sweeps. The journey will take six weeks. The pay is four dollars.","title":"Downriver","author":"Roughdraft Stories","description":"Samuel Corwin is eleven years old when he joins his uncle on a timber raft floating six hundred miles down the Mississippi River. It is 1854, and the raft moves only by the strength of twenty men pulling at the sweeps. The journey will take six weeks. The pay is four dollars.","ageRange":"8-10","genre":"Historical Fiction","tags":["historical","1850s","Mississippi River","logging","coming-of-age","work","family"],"coverImage":null,"chapters":[{"id":1,"number":1,"title":"The Last Pine","file":"chapter-1.md","markdown":"# The Last Pine\n\nThe last pine came down on a Tuesday morning in April. Samuel watched it fall. The tree was taller than any building he had ever seen, and when it hit the frozen ground the impact shook through his boots and up into his chest.\n\n\"That's the end of it,\" his father said. \"Camp's done.\"\n\nAll winter the logging crews had worked these woods, felling the great white pines and dragging them to the riverbank with teams of oxen. Now the hillsides stood bare and strange, nothing but stumps and slash where the forest had been. The logs lay stacked along the Chippewa River in long rows, waiting for the ice to break.\n\nSamuel was eleven years old. He had spent the winter helping his mother cook for the camp—peeling potatoes, hauling water, scrubbing pots in the cold. His father worked as a sawyer, one of the two-man teams that brought down the trees. The pay was good. By spring they would have enough money to buy seed for planting and maybe a new milk cow.\n\nBut now the work was finished, and Samuel's father would go back to the farm. Samuel would not.\n\n\"You sure about this?\" his father asked.\n\nSamuel nodded. He was not sure. He had never been less sure of anything in his life. But he said, \"Yes, sir.\"\n\nHis father looked at him for a long moment. Then he held out his hand. Samuel took it. His father's grip was hard and rough from the saw, and he shook Samuel's hand the way he would shake another man's.\n\n\"You do what your uncle tells you,\" his father said. \"You work hard and you don't complain. You understand?\"\n\n\"Yes, sir.\"\n\n\"Four dollars is good wages. You bring that money home.\"\n\n\"I will.\"\n\nHis mother was waiting by the cook shanty. She had a letter in her hand, already sealed and addressed. \"Mail this from Dubuque,\" she said. \"It's for your Aunt Ruth. Tell her we're well.\"\n\nSamuel put the letter inside his coat, close to his chest where it would stay dry. His mother's eyes were red but she was not crying. She kissed his forehead and held his face between her hands.\n\n\"You're a good boy,\" she said. \"You'll do fine.\"\n\nSamuel wanted to say something, but his throat felt tight and strange. He just nodded.\n\n---\n\nHis uncle was down by the river, watching the men build the raft.\n\nUncle Nate was his father's older brother. He was a raft pilot, which meant he knew the river from the Chippewa all the way down to St. Louis. He had made the trip nine times. He was a quiet man with a brown beard and eyes that seemed to be always looking at something far away.\n\n\"There you are,\" Uncle Nate said when Samuel walked up. \"Put your things in the wigwam. Second one from the front. Don't touch anything that isn't yours.\"\n\nThat was all. No greeting, no welcome. Samuel picked up his bundle—one change of clothes, a tin cup, and the pocketknife his father had given him for his birthday—and walked out onto the raft.\n\nIt was the strangest thing he had ever stood on. The raft was made of logs, hundreds of them, lashed together with rope and pinned with wooden pegs. The logs floated on the river, and the whole structure moved gently with the current, rocking like something alive.\n\nSamuel counted the sections as he walked. The men called them cribs. Each crib was about sixteen feet wide and thirty feet long, a little bigger than the cabin where he had been born. The cribs were fastened together in long rows called strings, and the strings were lashed side by side to make the raft.\n\nHe counted twelve strings. The raft was bigger than a barn. Bigger than a church. It was the largest thing Samuel had ever seen that could move.\n\nThe wigwams were canvas tents set up on wooden platforms in the middle of the raft. Samuel found the second one and ducked inside. It was small and dark and smelled of pine pitch and old smoke. Three bedrolls were already laid out on the plank floor. He put his bundle in the corner and went back outside.\n\nThe men were still working. At the front and back of the raft, crews were mounting the sweeps—huge oars, longer than the raft was wide, fixed to wooden posts so they could swing back and forth. It took four men to lift each sweep into place.\n\n\"You ever worked a sweep before?\"\n\nSamuel turned. A man was watching him, a big man with a red face and arms like tree trunks. He wore no coat despite the cold.\n\n\"No, sir.\"\n\n\"Didn't think so. You're Nate's nephew?\"\n\n\"Yes, sir.\"\n\n\"I'm Hendricks. I work the bow. You stay out of my way, you might learn something.\" He looked Samuel up and down. \"You know how to carry water?\"\n\n\"Yes, sir.\"\n\n\"Good. That's your job. You keep the water bucket full. When a man calls for water, you bring it. You don't spill it. Understand?\"\n\nSamuel understood. He had carried water all his life.\n\nThe work went on through the afternoon. Samuel stayed out of the way and watched. He counted twenty-two men, not including himself and Uncle Nate. Some were young, barely older than Samuel. Some were old, with gray beards and bent backs. They all worked without talking much, moving with the ease of men who had done this many times before.\n\nBy evening the raft was ready.\n\n---\n\nThey pushed off at dawn.\n\nSamuel stood near the front and watched the riverbank slide away. His parents were there, small figures growing smaller. His father raised one hand. His mother did not wave. She just stood there, watching, until the river bent and the trees came between them.\n\nThe raft moved without sound. That was the strange thing. Samuel had expected noise—creaking wood, splashing water, something. But there was only the soft push of current against the logs and the distant calls of the men at the sweeps.\n\n\"Hold her steady!\" That was Uncle Nate, standing on a platform in the middle of the raft where he could see the whole river ahead. \"Current's taking us. Let her ride!\"\n\nThe men at the sweeps leaned on the long oars, keeping the raft pointed downstream. The river was wide and brown with snowmelt, swollen with the spring thaw. On either bank the trees were just beginning to bud, pale green against the gray sky.\n\nSamuel found a place to sit where he was not in anyone's way. He watched the shore go by. He thought about his mother's letter, safe inside his coat. He thought about the four dollars he would earn if they made it to St. Louis.\n\nSix weeks, Uncle Nate had said. Maybe seven, depending on the river.\n\nSix weeks of this. Six weeks of water and work and sleeping on a pile of logs in the middle of the Mississippi River.\n\nSamuel took a deep breath. The air smelled like pine and cold water and something else—something he had no name for. The smell of going somewhere. The smell of a journey begun.\n\nThe raft floated on, and the river carried them south.\n","narration":null},{"id":2,"number":2,"title":"Learning the Sweeps","file":"chapter-2.md","markdown":"# Learning the Sweeps\n\nThe first morning, Samuel woke to the sound of men's voices and the smell of coffee.\n\nHe sat up in the dark of the wigwam. The other bedrolls were empty. Gray light showed through the canvas flap. He pulled on his boots and went outside.\n\nThe raft was moving. It had been moving all night. While Samuel slept, the men had kept working, steering the great mass of logs down the river in the dark. Now the eastern sky was pale with dawn, and the shore on either side was different from yesterday—lower, flatter, the trees smaller and farther apart.\n\n\"There's the boy.\" Hendricks was sitting by a small iron stove that had been set up near the cook's station. \"Thought you'd sleep through breakfast.\"\n\n\"What time is it?\"\n\n\"Time to eat, if you're hungry. Time to work, if you're not.\"\n\nSamuel ate. The cook was a thin man named Peterson who never seemed to talk. He gave Samuel a plate of salt pork and corn mush and a cup of black coffee. The coffee was bitter and too hot, but Samuel drank it because the other men did.\n\nAfter breakfast, Hendricks put him to work.\n\n\"Water bucket's there. Keep it full from the river. Use the rope—don't lean out too far or you'll fall in and we won't stop to fish you out.\" He was not joking. Samuel could tell.\n\nThe work was simple but endless. The men at the sweeps called for water every few minutes. They sweated even in the cold April air, straining against the heavy oars. Samuel brought them the bucket and the tin dipper, and they drank without stopping their work, then handed the dipper back and kept pulling.\n\nBy midday Samuel's arms ached from hauling the bucket up from the river. The rope burned his palms. He wrapped his hands in strips of cloth, the way he had seen the men wrap theirs, and kept working.\n\n---\n\nIn the afternoon, Uncle Nate called him over.\n\n\"Come here. Look.\"\n\nSamuel climbed up to the pilot's platform. It was a raised section in the middle of the raft, higher than a man's head, where Uncle Nate could see the river ahead. From up here, Samuel could see everything—the long stretch of brown water ahead, the wooded banks on either side, the men working at the sweeps below.\n\n\"See that?\" Uncle Nate pointed. \"That ripple in the water, there. What do you think that is?\"\n\nSamuel looked. He saw a faint line across the water, a place where the surface moved differently. \"I don't know.\"\n\n\"Sandbar. Just under the surface. Current's pushing over it. You see how the water moves?\"\n\nSamuel looked again. Now he could see it—the way the river's surface broke just slightly at that line, the way the current split around it.\n\n\"If we hit that, we run aground,\" Uncle Nate said. \"Take us half a day to get loose. Maybe lose some logs. You understand?\"\n\n\"Yes, sir.\"\n\n\"A raft pilot reads the water. He knows where the sandbars are, where the snags are, where the current runs deep. He knows by looking. You watch long enough, you start to see it.\"\n\nUncle Nate turned back to his work. \"Bow left!\" he shouted. \"Steady on the stern!\"\n\nThe men at the sweeps adjusted their pull, and the raft swung gently away from the rippling water. They passed the sandbar with room to spare.\n\nSamuel watched. He tried to see what Uncle Nate saw—the river as a map, a pattern, something that could be read like a page in a book. He could not see it yet. But he kept watching.\n\n---\n\nThe days took on a rhythm.\n\nSamuel woke before dawn and ate with the crew. He worked the water bucket until his arms burned. He watched the men at the sweeps, memorizing their movements—the way they leaned into the oars, the way they pulled in unison when Uncle Nate called out orders. In the afternoons, when the current ran smooth and easy, some of the men rested, sleeping on the logs or mending their clothes or playing cards in the shade of the wigwams.\n\nSamuel did not rest. He found work. He helped Peterson peel potatoes for supper. He coiled rope. He cleaned the rust off a spare sweep-pin with sand and a rag.\n\nHendricks noticed. He did not say anything, but he nodded once at Samuel, and after that he stopped calling him \"the boy.\"\n\n\"Your name's Samuel?\" he asked one evening.\n\n\"Yes, sir.\"\n\n\"You work hard, Samuel. That's good. Most boys your age, they complain. They want to rest. You keep working.\"\n\n\"My father said not to complain.\"\n\nHendricks laughed. It was a short, rough sound. \"Your father sounds like a sensible man.\"\n\n---\n\nOn the fifth day, Uncle Nate let Samuel touch the sweep.\n\n\"Come here,\" he said. \"Hendricks, give the boy your spot.\"\n\nHendricks stepped back, and Samuel took his place at the great oar. The sweep was made of pine, polished smooth by hundreds of hands. It was warm from the sun.\n\n\"Now pull,\" Uncle Nate said.\n\nSamuel pulled. The sweep did not move.\n\n\"Harder.\"\n\nHe pulled harder. His boots slid on the wet logs. The sweep trembled but barely shifted.\n\n\"That's fifty feet of oar and a thousand logs behind it,\" Uncle Nate said. \"You can't move it alone. That's why there's ten men on each sweep. You work together or you don't work at all. Now get back on the bucket.\"\n\nSamuel went back to carrying water. But he understood something now. The raft was not just wood and rope. It was weight. Impossible, enormous weight, and only the strength of men working together could make it go where it needed to go.\n\nThat night he lay in the wigwam and listened to the water beneath the logs. The raft moved on in the dark, carrying him south. He could feel the current through the wood, a steady pulse like a heartbeat.\n\nHe thought about his mother's letter, still safe in his coat. He thought about the four dollars. He thought about what Hendricks had said—*you work hard*.\n\nSamuel closed his eyes. His hands hurt and his back ached and his arms felt like they were made of lead. But he was not unhappy. He was doing real work, a man's work, and he was learning.\n\nTomorrow he would learn more.\n\nThe river carried them on.\n","narration":null},{"id":3,"number":3,"title":"The Snag","file":"chapter-3.md","markdown":"# The Snag\n\nIt happened on the eighth day, an hour before sunset.\n\nSamuel was bringing water to the stern crew when he heard Uncle Nate shout. It was not the normal call for the sweeps. It was something else—sharp, high, almost like the sound a man makes when he is hurt.\n\n\"Hard left! Hard left! Snag ahead!\"\n\nThe men at the bow sweeps threw their weight against the oars. The great beams swung wide. But the raft was too heavy, too slow. Samuel felt the current pulling them sideways. He saw the water ahead break and foam around something dark just below the surface.\n\nThe raft hit the snag.\n\nThe impact was not loud. That was the strange thing. Samuel had expected a crash, a boom, something that matched the size of what was happening. Instead there was only a deep, grinding crunch—the sound of wood meeting wood underwater—and then the whole raft shuddered.\n\nSamuel lost his footing. The water bucket flew from his hands and rolled across the logs. He fell hard on his side, the breath knocked out of him.\n\n\"Check the lashings! Check the lashings now!\"\n\nMen were running. Samuel pushed himself up and saw Hendricks sprinting toward the starboard side, where the raft's edge met the river. Other men followed. Samuel got to his feet and ran after them.\n\nThe snag had caught them on the right side, near the back. It was a dead tree, a great pine that must have fallen into the river upstream and floated down until it lodged in the riverbed. The top of the trunk still showed above the water, white and bare, stripped of bark. The roots were underwater, invisible, and they had torn into the raft like claws.\n\n\"We're losing the seventh string!\" someone shouted.\n\nSamuel could see it now. The seventh string—twelve cribs lashed together in a long row—had broken loose. The rope that held it to the rest of the raft had snapped. The string was drifting away, pulled by the current, spinning slowly as it went.\n\n\"Get the rope! Get the rope!\"\n\nHendricks grabbed a coil of hemp rope and threw one end toward the drifting string. The rope uncoiled in the air, spinning out over the brown water. It fell short. The string kept drifting.\n\nA young man—his name was Paulsen—ran to the edge of the raft and jumped. He hit the water and went under, then came up gasping. He swam hard toward the loose string, fighting the current.\n\n\"Throw him the line! Throw him the line!\"\n\nHendricks threw again. This time the rope reached Paulsen. He caught it with one hand and kept swimming with the other. When he reached the loose string he pulled himself up onto the logs, wrapped the rope around a peg, and held on.\n\n\"Pull! All hands pull!\"\n\nSamuel grabbed the rope. So did everyone else. Twenty men hauled on the line, leaning back, digging their heels into the logs. The loose string fought them. The current pulled at it. The rope creaked and groaned.\n\nSlowly, foot by foot, they pulled the string back.\n\nIt took an hour. Samuel's hands burned. The rope tore at his palms, wearing through the cloth he had wrapped around them. Blood seeped into the fibers. He did not let go.\n\nWhen the string was finally close enough to lash back to the raft, Hendricks and two other men jumped across to secure it. They worked fast, tying new knots, driving new pegs. The sun was setting by the time they finished, the sky going red and gold in the west.\n\n---\n\nUncle Nate called a halt for the night.\n\nThey poled the raft toward the shore and tied it to trees on the bank. No one had ever done that before—every other night they had kept moving, steering through the dark. But the snag had damaged the lashings in three places, and they needed time to make repairs.\n\nSamuel sat on a crib near the edge of the raft and looked at his hands. The cloth wrappings were soaked with blood. His palms were raw, the skin torn away in strips.\n\n\"Let me see.\"\n\nPeterson, the cook, crouched beside him. He took Samuel's hands and turned them over, studying the damage in the fading light.\n\n\"Not too bad,\" he said. \"I've seen worse.\"\n\n\"It hurts.\"\n\n\"It will hurt more tomorrow.\" Peterson unwrapped the bloody cloth and threw it into the river. He pulled a small tin from his pocket and opened it. Inside was a thick yellow grease that smelled like pine tar and something else, something sharp. \"Hold still.\"\n\nHe smeared the grease across Samuel's palms. It stung fiercely, worse than the rope burn, and Samuel clenched his jaw to keep from crying out.\n\n\"That's good,\" Peterson said. \"Means it's working. Keep your hands clean tonight. No water work tomorrow. Understand?\"\n\n\"Yes, sir.\"\n\nPeterson wrapped Samuel's hands in fresh cloth and stood up. \"You did good,\" he said. \"Most boys would have let go.\"\n\nHe walked away before Samuel could answer.\n\n---\n\nThat night they ate cold food. Peterson did not light the stove. The men sat in small groups, talking quietly, chewing on hard biscuit and dried beef. Some of them looked at the place where the snag had hit, the broken ropes and splintered wood still visible in the moonlight.\n\nUncle Nate came and sat beside Samuel.\n\n\"How are your hands?\"\n\n\"They hurt.\"\n\n\"They'll hurt for a while.\" Uncle Nate was quiet for a moment. \"You held the rope. I saw you.\"\n\nSamuel did not know what to say. He had held the rope because everyone else was holding it. There had been nothing else to do.\n\n\"Some men let go,\" Uncle Nate said. \"When it hurts, when it gets hard, they let go. They think someone else will hold on for them.\" He looked at Samuel in the dark. \"You didn't let go.\"\n\n\"No, sir.\"\n\n\"That's what matters. Out here, that's the only thing that matters.\" Uncle Nate stood up. \"Get some sleep. We push off at first light.\"\n\nSamuel lay in the wigwam and listened to the river. His hands throbbed. When he closed his eyes, he saw the loose string drifting away, spinning in the current. He saw Paulsen jumping into the water. He felt the rope burning through his palms.\n\nBut they had not lost the string. Twenty men pulling together had brought it back.\n\nSamuel flexed his bandaged hands. The pain was sharp and clean, and underneath it was something else—something that felt almost like pride.\n\nHe slept.\n","narration":null},{"id":4,"number":4,"title":"Dubuque","file":"chapter-4.md","markdown":"# Dubuque\n\nThey saw Dubuque from five miles upriver.\n\nThe city rose on bluffs above the water, white buildings and church steeples catching the afternoon sun. Smoke drifted from chimneys. Samuel could see boats tied up along the waterfront—steamboats with their tall stacks, flatboats piled with cargo, and other rafts like their own, some even bigger.\n\n\"We'll stop here overnight,\" Uncle Nate said. \"Sell off two strings. Take on supplies.\"\n\nThe men cheered. Samuel understood why. Two weeks on the river, sleeping on logs, eating the same food every day. A night in town meant solid ground. It meant hot food cooked by someone else. For some of the men, it meant other things—Samuel had heard them talking about taverns and card games—but he did not care about any of that.\n\nHe just wanted to mail his mother's letter.\n\n---\n\nThey tied up at the lumber wharf in the late afternoon. Buyers were waiting—men in good coats with paper and pencils, walking along the edge of the raft, looking at the logs.\n\n\"Good pine,\" Samuel heard one of them say. \"Clean grain. How much for the lot?\"\n\n\"We're not selling the lot,\" Uncle Nate said. \"Two strings. That's what I can spare.\"\n\nThey haggled. Samuel watched. Uncle Nate's face never changed, but his voice got quieter and slower the longer they talked. Finally the buyer nodded and pulled out a leather wallet. He counted bills into Uncle Nate's hand.\n\n\"Pleasure doing business,\" the buyer said.\n\n\"Likewise.\"\n\nThe buyer walked away. Uncle Nate counted the money again, folded it, and put it inside his coat.\n\n\"Paulsen, Hendricks—unlash the two stern strings. The rest of you, you've got until dawn. Don't get arrested.\"\n\nThe men scattered. Some headed up the bluff toward town. Others stayed on the raft, sleeping or mending clothes. Samuel stood at the edge of the wharf, looking at the city.\n\n\"You going up?\" Hendricks asked.\n\n\"Yes, sir. I have a letter to mail.\"\n\n\"Post office is on Main Street. Turn left at the top of the hill, keep walking. You can't miss it.\" Hendricks looked at him. \"You have money?\"\n\nSamuel shook his head.\n\nHendricks reached into his pocket and pulled out a coin. \"Two cents for the postage. Get yourself a bun at the bakery next door. You look hungry.\"\n\n\"I can't take your money.\"\n\n\"You can pay me back out of your wages in St. Louis.\" Hendricks pressed the coin into Samuel's bandaged hand. \"Go on. Be back by dark.\"\n\n---\n\nWalking on solid ground felt wrong.\n\nSamuel's legs had grown used to the constant movement of the raft, the gentle rocking of the logs beneath his feet. Now the street was hard and still, and his body kept expecting it to shift. He stumbled twice on the way up the hill.\n\nDubuque was the biggest town Samuel had ever seen. There were buildings three and four stories tall, built of brick and stone. There were shops with glass windows and signs painted in gold letters. There were people everywhere—men in suits, women in long dresses, children running and shouting. A wagon rattled past, pulled by two gray horses. A dog barked from an alley.\n\nThe sounds were too loud. The smells were too strong. After two weeks of pine and river water, the city seemed to press in from every side.\n\nSamuel found the post office. It was a small building with a flag out front. Inside, a man sat behind a counter, sorting letters into wooden boxes.\n\n\"Help you?\"\n\nSamuel pulled the letter from inside his coat. It was creased and soft from being carried so long, but the ink was still clear. \"I need to mail this. To Wisconsin.\"\n\nThe man looked at the address. \"Three cents.\"\n\n\"I only have two.\"\n\nThe man studied Samuel for a moment—his rough clothes, his bandaged hands, the sunburn on his face. \"Where you coming from?\"\n\n\"The Chippewa. I'm on a raft, going to St. Louis.\"\n\n\"Raftsman, huh?\" The man almost smiled. \"Two cents is fine. We'll call it a discount for the working man.\"\n\nHe took the letter and put it in one of the boxes. Samuel watched it go. In a week, maybe less, his mother would hold that letter in her hands. She would know he was safe. She would know he had made it this far.\n\n\"Thank you,\" Samuel said.\n\n\"Safe travels, son.\"\n\n---\n\nThe bakery was next door, just like Hendricks had said. Samuel bought a sweet bun with the penny he had left. He ate it standing on the sidewalk, watching the people go by.\n\nA boy about his age walked past with a fishing pole over his shoulder. Two girls in matching blue dresses skipped by, laughing at some joke. A man pushed a cart loaded with apples, calling out his prices in a loud, singing voice.\n\nThey all looked so clean. So rested. Their hands were not bandaged. Their clothes were not stiff with river water and pine pitch.\n\nSamuel finished his bun and walked back down the hill toward the wharf.\n\n---\n\nThe raft looked smaller tied up at the dock. In the middle of the river it had seemed enormous, a whole world floating on the water. Here, next to the steamboats and the brick warehouses, it was just a pile of logs held together with rope.\n\nBut it was home now. Samuel realized that as he stepped back onto the deck. The slight give of the logs beneath his feet, the smell of wood and water, the sound of the river moving past—it all felt right in a way that the city streets had not.\n\nHendricks was sitting by the cook's stove, cleaning his boots.\n\n\"Mail your letter?\"\n\n\"Yes, sir.\"\n\n\"Good.\" Hendricks looked up. \"How was the town?\"\n\nSamuel thought about it. The noise. The crowds. The boy with the fishing pole.\n\n\"Too still,\" he said.\n\nHendricks laughed. \"That's what they all say. First time in town after a week on the river, it feels like the ground's broken. Like something's missing.\"\n\n\"What's missing?\"\n\n\"The current.\" Hendricks went back to cleaning his boots. \"Out here, we're always moving. Even when we're standing still, the river's carrying us. Town doesn't move. That's why it feels wrong.\"\n\nSamuel nodded. He understood.\n\nThat night he slept better than he had since they left Wisconsin. The raft rocked gently against the dock, and the river whispered beneath the logs, and in his dreams he was still moving, still going south, still on his way.\n","narration":null},{"id":5,"number":5,"title":"The Man Who Fell","file":"chapter-5.md","markdown":"# The Man Who Fell\n\nThe morning after they left Dubuque, the river turned.\n\nSamuel had grown used to the wide, straight stretches where the current ran smooth and easy. Now the Mississippi bent and twisted, curving around islands thick with willows. The water moved faster here, and the men at the sweeps worked harder to keep the raft in the channel.\n\n\"Watch the right bank!\" Uncle Nate called. \"Current's pushing us wide!\"\n\nThe bow crew leaned into their sweep. The stern crew pulled the opposite way. The raft turned slowly, slowly, the logs groaning against each other.\n\nThat was when Garrett fell.\n\nGarrett was one of the younger men, maybe eighteen or nineteen. He worked the stern sweep, and he was good at it—quick on his feet, strong in the arms. Samuel had watched him jump from crib to crib during the snag crisis, sure-footed as a cat.\n\nBut the logs were wet that morning. Rain had fallen in the night, and the deck was slick with water. When Garrett stepped back to brace for a pull, his boot slipped.\n\nSamuel saw it happen. Garrett's arms went wide. His face changed—not fear, not yet, just surprise. Then he went down, hard, and his body hit the gap between two logs and kept going.\n\nHe went into the river.\n\n\"Man overboard! Man overboard!\"\n\nThe shout went up from three men at once. Samuel was already running. He did not think about what he was doing. He just ran toward the place where Garrett had gone down.\n\nThe logs were moving. That was the terrible thing. The raft did not stop. The river pushed it forward, and the gap where Garrett had fallen was sliding away, moving toward the back of the raft.\n\nSamuel reached the edge and looked down. He could see the water churning between the logs—brown and fast, flecked with white foam. He could not see Garrett.\n\n\"There!\" Someone grabbed Samuel's arm and pointed. \"He's under the stern string!\"\n\nGarrett had surfaced behind the raft. He was in the water, his head just visible above the chop. One arm was waving. The other was not moving at all.\n\nHendricks threw a rope. It landed short. He hauled it back, coiled it, threw again. This time it hit the water near Garrett's waving hand.\n\n\"Grab it! Grab the rope!\"\n\nGarrett grabbed. Hendricks and two other men pulled. Samuel ran to help, wrapping his still-healing hands around the wet hemp.\n\nThey hauled Garrett in like a fish. He came up over the edge of the raft gasping, shaking, water streaming from his clothes. His left arm hung at a wrong angle, the elbow bent where no elbow should bend.\n\n\"He's hurt,\" someone said.\n\n\"Get him to the cook's station,\" Uncle Nate ordered. \"Peterson—you know how to set a bone?\"\n\n\"I've done it before.\"\n\n---\n\nThey laid Garrett on the planks by the stove. His face was white, and he was breathing in short, quick gasps. His broken arm lay across his chest like something dead.\n\nPeterson knelt beside him. He felt along the arm with careful fingers, starting at the shoulder and working down. When he reached the elbow, Garrett cried out.\n\n\"It's bad,\" Peterson said. \"Dislocated at the elbow, maybe broken above it too.\" He looked at Uncle Nate. \"I can set it, but he won't work again this trip.\"\n\n\"Do what you have to do.\"\n\nPeterson turned to Samuel. \"Hold his good arm. Hold it tight. Don't let him move.\"\n\nSamuel knelt and took Garrett's right hand. Garrett's fingers closed around his, squeezing hard.\n\n\"Look at me,\" Samuel said. He did not know why he said it. The words just came. \"Don't look at what he's doing. Look at me.\"\n\nGarrett looked at him. His eyes were wide with pain and fear.\n\nPeterson grabbed Garrett's broken arm with both hands. There was a sound—a wet, grinding pop—and Garrett screamed. His whole body arched off the planks. His grip on Samuel's hand went so tight that Samuel felt the bones grind together.\n\nThen it was over. Garrett collapsed, panting. His arm was straight again, or nearly straight. Peterson was wrapping it with strips of canvas, binding it to a flat piece of wood.\n\n\"He'll live,\" Peterson said. \"But that arm needs a real doctor. He's done working.\"\n\n---\n\nGarrett rode the rest of the way in the wigwam.\n\nThe other men took turns checking on him, bringing him water and food. Samuel helped. He changed the bandages when they got dirty. He sat with Garrett in the afternoons when the work was slow, listening to him talk about his family back in Wisconsin—a mother, two sisters, a farm that never quite made enough.\n\n\"Four dollars would have helped,\" Garrett said one afternoon. His voice was quiet, tired. \"That's why I signed on. Four dollars for six weeks' work.\"\n\n\"You'll still get paid,\" Samuel said. \"Won't you?\"\n\nGarrett shrugged with his good shoulder. \"Maybe. If Nate's fair about it. I didn't finish the work.\"\n\nSamuel did not know what to say. He thought about his own four dollars, waiting for him in St. Louis. He thought about what would happen if he fell, if his arm broke, if he could not work.\n\n\"I'm sorry,\" he said.\n\nGarrett looked at him. \"It's not your fault. It's no one's fault. The logs were wet. I slipped.\" He closed his eyes. \"That's how it happens out here. One wrong step.\"\n\n---\n\nAfter Garrett's fall, Uncle Nate moved Samuel to the stern sweep.\n\n\"You're not strong enough to pull full weight,\" he said. \"But you can stand with the crew. You can learn the rhythm. When they pull, you pull. Understand?\"\n\n\"Yes, sir.\"\n\nSamuel took his place at the end of the great oar. Hendricks stood beside him, and three other men beyond. The sweep was heavy in his hands, heavier than he remembered from the day Uncle Nate had let him try it.\n\n\"Ready?\" Hendricks said.\n\n\"Ready.\"\n\n\"Pull!\"\n\nThey pulled together. Samuel felt the resistance—the weight of the logs, the push of the current—and he threw his whole body into the oar. It was not enough. His pull was nothing compared to the men beside him. But it was something.\n\n\"Again! Pull!\"\n\nThey pulled again. The raft shifted, turning slightly in the channel.\n\n\"Good!\" Uncle Nate called from the pilot's platform. \"Hold her steady!\"\n\nSamuel held. His arms burned. His hands ached. But he was working the sweep now. He was part of the crew.\n\nThat night Hendricks sat with him at supper.\n\n\"You did all right today,\" he said.\n\n\"I didn't do much.\"\n\n\"You did what you could.\" Hendricks chewed his salt pork slowly. \"That's all any of us do. You think I can pull as hard as Paulsen? He's got fifty pounds on me. But I pull what I can, and he pulls what he can, and together we move the raft.\" He looked at Samuel. \"That's the whole trick, son. Nobody does it alone.\"\n\nSamuel nodded. He understood.\n\nFrom now on, he would pull with the crew.\n","narration":null},{"id":6,"number":6,"title":"Rock Island Rapids","file":"chapter-6.md","markdown":"# Rock Island Rapids\n\nThey heard the rapids before they saw them.\n\nSamuel was at his place on the stern sweep when the sound reached him—a low, steady roar, like wind through pines but deeper. He looked at Hendricks.\n\n\"Rapids,\" Hendricks said. \"Rock Island. Fifteen miles of bad water.\"\n\nSamuel had heard the men talk about the rapids. They spoke of them the way his father spoke about winter storms—with respect and a little fear. Even experienced pilots lost rafts here. Logs broke loose. Men drowned.\n\n\"We'll need a guide,\" Uncle Nate said. \"There's a town up ahead. LeClaire. The rapids pilots live there.\"\n\nThey tied up at LeClaire that afternoon. It was a small town, smaller than Dubuque, built on a flat stretch of riverbank just above the rough water. Samuel could see the rapids from the wharf—a stretch of white and brown where the river broke over rocks, churning and foaming for as far as he could see.\n\nUncle Nate went into town alone. He came back an hour later with a man Samuel had never seen before.\n\n\"This is Captain Rambo,\" Uncle Nate said. \"He'll take us through.\"\n\nCaptain Rambo was an old man, maybe sixty, with a white beard and eyes that looked like they had seen everything the river could do and were not impressed. He walked across the raft without hurrying, studying the logs, testing the lashings.\n\n\"Good raft,\" he said finally. \"Well made. Who built it?\"\n\n\"Camp foreman named Bjornson,\" Uncle Nate said. \"Up on the Chippewa.\"\n\n\"He knows his business.\" Captain Rambo squinted at the rapids ahead. \"We'll go at first light. The morning current runs cleaner. I want every man at the sweeps. No exceptions.\"\n\nHe looked at Samuel.\n\n\"You too, boy. You'll work or you'll stay here. Your choice.\"\n\n\"I'll work,\" Samuel said.\n\n\"Good.\" Captain Rambo almost smiled. \"Get some sleep. Tomorrow will be long.\"\n\n---\n\nThey pushed off at dawn.\n\nThe river was silver in the early light, the air cold and still. Captain Rambo stood on the pilot's platform beside Uncle Nate, but there was no question who was in charge now. When Captain Rambo spoke, Uncle Nate listened.\n\n\"Easy on the bow! Let the current take us!\"\n\nThe sweeps went still. The raft drifted forward, picking up speed as it approached the white water.\n\nSamuel could feel the change beneath his feet. The logs began to move differently—not the gentle rocking he was used to, but a harder, more urgent motion. The raft was no longer floating. It was being pulled.\n\n\"Hard left! Now!\"\n\nThe bow crew threw their weight against the sweep. Samuel pulled with the stern crew, every muscle straining. The raft turned, barely, slipping past a dark shape in the water—a boulder, just under the surface.\n\n\"Hold! Hold steady!\"\n\nThey held. The current grabbed the raft and yanked it forward. Samuel saw white water explode around the edges of the logs. Spray hit his face, cold as ice.\n\n\"Right! Hard right!\"\n\nThey pulled the other way. The raft swung. Another rock slid past, so close that Samuel could have touched it.\n\nAnd then they were in the middle of the rapids.\n\nThe noise was everywhere. Samuel could not hear the orders anymore—only the roar of water over stone, the crash of the current against the logs. He watched Hendricks and pulled when Hendricks pulled, held when Hendricks held. The sweep bucked in his hands like a living thing.\n\nThe raft bucked and shuddered. Water washed over the deck. Samuel's boots were soaked. His grip on the sweep was slipping. He wrapped his arms around the oar and held on with his whole body.\n\nA log broke loose. Samuel saw it go—a single pine, spinning away into the white water. It hit a rock and shattered, splinters flying. Gone.\n\n\"Keep pulling! Don't stop!\"\n\nThey did not stop. Samuel's arms screamed. His shoulders burned. The world was nothing but water and noise and the desperate pull of the sweep.\n\nAnd then, suddenly, it was over.\n\nThe raft shot out of the rapids into calm water. The roar faded behind them. The river stretched ahead, smooth and brown and quiet.\n\nSamuel collapsed against the sweep, gasping. His whole body was shaking.\n\nAround him, the men were cheering. Hendricks was laughing, slapping Paulsen on the back. Even Peterson was smiling. They had made it. They were through.\n\nCaptain Rambo climbed down from the pilot's platform. He walked to the edge of the raft and looked back at the rapids, now just a distant white line across the river.\n\n\"Good work,\" he said. \"One log lost. Could have been worse. Could have been a lot worse.\"\n\nHe turned and shook Uncle Nate's hand. \"You've got a good crew. That boy included.\" He nodded at Samuel. \"He didn't let go.\"\n\n\"No,\" Uncle Nate said. \"He didn't.\"\n\n---\n\nThey dropped Captain Rambo at Rock Island, the town that gave the rapids their name. Uncle Nate paid him in coins from the leather wallet, and the old man walked off down the dock without looking back.\n\nSamuel stood at the edge of the raft and watched the rapids grow smaller in the distance. In a few hours they would be gone from sight. In a few days he would not be able to hear them anymore.\n\nBut he would never forget them.\n\n\"First time through?\" Hendricks stood beside him, looking back at the white water.\n\n\"Yes, sir.\"\n\n\"How did it feel?\"\n\nSamuel thought about it. The fear. The noise. The moment when his grip started to slip and he thought he was going to fall.\n\n\"I thought we were going to die,\" he said.\n\nHendricks nodded. \"We all think that, first time through. Second time too. Third time, you start to realize that thinking you're going to die and actually dying are two different things.\" He clapped Samuel on the shoulder. \"You did good. Now get some rest. The river runs smooth for a while.\"\n\nSamuel found a dry spot on the logs and sat down. The sun was warm on his face. The raft rocked gently on the calm water.\n\nHe was not the same boy who had left Wisconsin. He could feel the difference. Something had changed—not just his body, with its new calluses and aching muscles, but something inside.\n\nHe had been afraid, and he had kept working.\n\nHe had felt his grip slipping, and he had held on.\n\nThat was something. That meant something.\n\nSamuel closed his eyes and let the sun dry his clothes. The river carried them south.\n","narration":null},{"id":7,"number":7,"title":"Night Storm","file":"chapter-7.md","markdown":"# Night Storm\n\nThe storm came from the west.\n\nSamuel saw it building all afternoon—a dark line on the horizon, growing taller as the hours passed. The clouds were the color of bruises, purple and green and gray. Lightning flickered in the distance, too far away to hear.\n\n\"We should tie up,\" Hendricks said, looking at the sky. \"Find a bank and wait it out.\"\n\nUncle Nate shook his head. \"No good banks through here. Bluffs on both sides, and the current runs too fast. We'd get pinned against the rocks.\"\n\n\"So we ride it out?\"\n\n\"We ride it out.\"\n\nThey passed Quincy in the late afternoon. Samuel saw the town lights come on as the darkness spread across the sky. Part of him wished they would stop there, tie up at a safe dock, wait in a warm building until the storm passed.\n\nBut the raft kept moving. The river carried them south, and the storm came to meet them.\n\n---\n\nIt hit just after sunset.\n\nThe wind arrived first—a hard gust that snapped the canvas of the wigwams and nearly knocked Samuel off his feet. Then the rain came, not in drops but in sheets, so thick he could barely see the bow of the raft from where he stood.\n\n\"All hands to the sweeps! Hold her steady!\"\n\nSamuel ran to his place. The sweep was slick with rain, hard to grip. He wrapped his arms around it and held on.\n\nThe river had changed. It was no longer brown and smooth. It was black and wild, churned up by the wind, waves rising and crashing over the logs. The raft pitched and rolled. Samuel felt his stomach lurch.\n\nLightning split the sky, so bright it left spots in his eyes. The thunder came half a second later, a crack that shook the air and rattled his teeth.\n\n\"Pull! Pull and hold!\"\n\nThey pulled. The sweep fought them, jerking in their hands as the waves hit. Samuel's feet slid on the wet logs. He dug in with his heels and kept pulling.\n\nAnother flash of lightning. In its light Samuel saw the river ahead—a chaos of white-capped waves, the shore invisible in the rain. They were in the middle of nowhere, alone on the water, with nothing to do but hold on.\n\n\"We're drifting left! Bow crew, pull hard! Hard!\"\n\nThe bow crew strained against their sweep. The raft turned, slowly, fighting the wind. Samuel could feel the logs grinding against each other, the lashings creaking.\n\nA wave broke over the deck. Cold water hit Samuel's chest, nearly lifting him off his feet. He gasped, choked, kept holding the sweep.\n\n\"Don't let go!\" Hendricks shouted in his ear. \"Whatever you do, don't let go!\"\n\nSamuel did not let go. His hands were numb. His arms were shaking. The sweep was the only solid thing in a world of wind and water and noise.\n\nThe storm went on.\n\n---\n\nHours passed. Or maybe it was minutes. Samuel could not tell. Time had stopped meaning anything. There was only the next wave, the next gust of wind, the next flash of lightning that showed the world in frozen white.\n\nAt some point he realized he was crying. The tears mixed with the rain on his face. He did not stop working.\n\nThe wigwam next to him tore loose. He saw it happen—the canvas ripping free of its ropes, flying up into the dark like a ghost. It was there and then it was gone, swallowed by the storm.\n\n\"Let it go! Stay on the sweep!\"\n\nSamuel stayed. The raft bucked beneath him. A crib somewhere behind them was taking on water, the logs riding lower than they should. Men were shouting, but he could not hear the words over the wind.\n\nAnd then, slowly, the storm began to pass.\n\nThe rain eased. The wind dropped. The lightning moved east, the flashes growing fainter, the thunder fading to a distant rumble.\n\nSamuel stood at the sweep, blinking. His whole body ached. He could not feel his hands.\n\nThe sky was gray now, not black. He could see the shore—a dark line of trees on either side of the river. They were still in the channel. They had not run aground.\n\n\"Easy on the sweeps,\" Uncle Nate called. His voice was hoarse, tired. \"Let her ride. We're through.\"\n\n---\n\nThe dawn came gray and cold.\n\nSamuel sat on a crib near the bow, wrapped in a wet blanket. He was too tired to sleep. Too tired to move. He just sat there, watching the light grow in the east.\n\nThey had lost one wigwam and half their supplies. The cook's stove had gone over the side in the night, and Peterson was already talking about how they would manage without it. Cold food for the rest of the trip. No hot coffee.\n\nBut the raft was whole. The lashings had held. No one had fallen overboard.\n\nUncle Nate came and sat beside him. He did not say anything for a long time. They watched the sun rise together, a pale disk behind the clouds.\n\nThen Uncle Nate put his hand on Samuel's shoulder.\n\nHe did not squeeze. He did not pat. He just rested his hand there, heavy and warm, and left it for a moment.\n\nThen he stood up and walked back to the pilot's platform.\n\nSamuel understood. That was the thing about Uncle Nate—he did not use words when he did not need them. The hand on the shoulder said everything.\n\n*You did well.*\n\n*I'm proud of you.*\n\n*You belong here.*\n\nSamuel pulled the wet blanket tighter around his shoulders and watched the river unfold ahead. St. Louis was close now. A few more days. A week at most.\n\nThe worst was behind them.\n\nThe river carried them on.\n","narration":null},{"id":8,"number":8,"title":"St. Louis","file":"chapter-8.md","markdown":"# St. Louis\n\nThey saw St. Louis on a clear May morning, six weeks after leaving Wisconsin.\n\nSamuel stood at the bow and watched the city grow out of the bluffs. It was enormous—bigger than anything he had imagined, bigger than Dubuque and Rock Island and every town they had passed combined. Buildings rose in layers up the hillside, brick and stone and painted wood. Church steeples pierced the sky. Smoke drifted from a hundred chimneys.\n\nAnd the river was crowded with boats.\n\nSamuel counted twelve steamboats at the wharves, their tall stacks belching black smoke. Flatboats piled with cargo rode low in the water. Smaller craft darted between the larger vessels—rowboats, fishing boats, ferries crossing to the far shore. And rafts. There were other rafts, some as big as their own, tied up along the lumber docks.\n\n\"That's it,\" Hendricks said, standing beside him. \"That's where we've been heading.\"\n\n\"It's big.\"\n\n\"Biggest city on the river. Maybe the biggest city in the country, I don't know. Never been anywhere else.\"\n\nUncle Nate guided them in. It took nearly an hour to work the raft through the traffic, steering around the steamboats and their churning paddle wheels. By the time they tied up at the lumber wharf, the sun was high overhead.\n\nThe buyers were waiting.\n\n---\n\nSamuel watched Uncle Nate work.\n\nThe buyers walked along the edge of the raft, just like in Dubuque, looking at the logs. But there were more of them here, and they asked more questions. How old was the timber? Where was it cut? How long had it been in the water?\n\nUncle Nate answered everything. He knew the trees by name—white pine, red pine, the occasional oak that had been mixed in. He knew how many board feet each log would yield. He knew the going rate and when to argue and when to stay quiet.\n\n\"Fifteen dollars per thousand feet,\" one buyer offered.\n\n\"Eighteen,\" Uncle Nate said.\n\n\"That's too high. I can get Wisconsin pine from three other rafts today.\"\n\n\"Then buy from them.\" Uncle Nate did not raise his voice. \"But their pine isn't as clean as mine. No knots. No rot. Look for yourself.\"\n\nThe buyer looked. He walked down the length of the raft, examining log after log. Finally he came back.\n\n\"Seventeen.\"\n\n\"Done.\"\n\nThey shook hands. The buyer called for his crew, and men with long poles and hooks began rolling the logs off the raft, sending them splashing into the water where other men caught them and guided them toward the shore.\n\nSamuel watched the raft shrink. String by string, the logs he had floated with for six weeks were pulled away. By late afternoon, there was nothing left but the platform they stood on—the frame and the wigwams and the place where the cook's stove had been before the storm took it.\n\n\"That's it,\" Uncle Nate said. \"We're done.\"\n\n---\n\nThey settled accounts on the wharf.\n\nThe buyer paid in cash—a thick stack of bills that Uncle Nate counted twice before putting in his wallet. Then Uncle Nate turned to the crew.\n\n\"Line up. Everyone gets their share.\"\n\nThe men lined up. One by one, they stepped forward, and Uncle Nate counted out their wages. Some got more, some less—it depended on their job, how many runs they'd made, whether they had any debts against their pay.\n\nGarrett was near the front. His arm was still in the sling, and his face was pale, but he stood straight.\n\n\"Half wages,\" Uncle Nate said. \"You worked half the trip.\"\n\n\"That's fair,\" Garrett said. He took the money and walked away without looking back.\n\nSamuel watched him go. Half wages was two dollars. Two dollars for an arm that might never work right again.\n\n\"Samuel Corwin.\"\n\nSamuel stepped forward. Uncle Nate looked at him for a long moment.\n\n\"You signed on to carry water. I put you on the sweep instead. You worked the rapids. You worked the storm.\" Uncle Nate reached into the stack of bills and pulled out four silver dollars. \"Full wages.\"\n\nHe put the coins in Samuel's hand.\n\nThey were heavy. Samuel had held coins before, but never like this. These were his. He had earned them.\n\n\"Thank you,\" he said.\n\nUncle Nate nodded. \"You did the work. The pay's not thanks—it's what you earned.\"\n\n---\n\nThe crew scattered after that.\n\nSome headed into the city, looking for food or drink or beds in boarding houses. Some had family in St. Louis and went to find them. Some, like Hendricks, would sign on to another raft heading back upriver, making the trip in reverse.\n\nSamuel stood on the empty wharf and looked at the city.\n\n\"What now?\" he asked.\n\nUncle Nate was checking his wallet, making sure everything was in order. \"Now we go home. Steamboat to Muscatine, then we walk. Should take two weeks, maybe less.\"\n\n\"Two weeks.\"\n\n\"Your mother will be glad to see you.\" Uncle Nate looked at him. \"Your father too.\"\n\nSamuel thought about the farm. The small house. The field that needed planting, the cow that needed milking. It felt far away, like something from another life.\n\nBut it was still home. And he was going back to it.\n\n\"When do we leave?\"\n\n\"Tomorrow morning. First boat north.\" Uncle Nate put his wallet away. \"Tonight, we eat. Real food, cooked on a real stove. And then we sleep in real beds. You've earned that much.\"\n\nThey walked up from the wharf together, into the city. Samuel's four dollars were heavy in his pocket. His hands were calloused, his shoulders were sore, and his boots had holes that let in water.\n\nBut he was walking like a man who had done a man's work.\n\nAnd that was worth more than any four dollars could buy.\n","narration":null},{"id":9,"number":9,"title":"The Walk Home","file":"chapter-9.md","markdown":"# The Walk Home\n\nThe steamboat carried them north for three days.\n\nSamuel stood at the rail and watched the river unwind beneath them. The boat moved fast, faster than the raft had ever moved—pushed by great paddle wheels that churned the brown water white. Towns slid past. Bluffs rose and fell. The same miles that had taken him six weeks to travel downriver now vanished in hours.\n\nIt felt wrong, somehow. Too fast. Too easy.\n\nAt Muscatine they left the steamboat. Uncle Nate paid for passage as far as the money would take them, but it would not take them all the way home. The last hundred miles they would walk.\n\n\"Ready?\" Uncle Nate asked.\n\nSamuel shouldered his bundle—still just one change of clothes, a tin cup, and his pocketknife, the same as when he left. The clothes were worn now, patched in places. The cup was dented. The knife had been sharpened so many times that the blade was half as wide as it had been in April.\n\n\"Ready,\" he said.\n\nThey walked.\n\n---\n\nThe road wound through farmland and forest, following the river valleys north and west. They slept in barns when farmers let them, and under trees when they did not. Uncle Nate knew the way. He had walked this road nine times before.\n\nThey did not talk much. There was no need. After six weeks on the raft, they had grown used to each other's silence.\n\nBut on the fourth night, sitting by a small fire in a clearing, Uncle Nate spoke.\n\n\"You did well.\"\n\nSamuel looked at him. The firelight made deep shadows on Uncle Nate's face.\n\n\"Thank you.\"\n\n\"I wasn't sure about bringing you. You're young. It's hard work. Most boys your age, they can't handle it.\" Uncle Nate poked at the fire with a stick. \"But your father said you were ready. He was right.\"\n\nSamuel thought about his father. The handshake before he left. *You do what your uncle tells you. You don't complain.*\n\n\"Will you take another raft down next year?\" Samuel asked.\n\n\"Probably. The timber's getting thin up on the Chippewa, but there's still enough for a few more years. After that, I don't know. Maybe the railroads will take over.\" Uncle Nate shrugged. \"Things change. The river stays the same, but everything else changes.\"\n\nThey sat in silence for a while. The fire crackled. Somewhere in the dark, an owl called.\n\n\"Could I come with you?\" Samuel asked. \"Next year, I mean.\"\n\nUncle Nate looked at him. His eyes were steady, unreadable.\n\n\"Ask your father,\" he said. \"If he says yes, there's a place for you.\"\n\nThat was all. But it was enough.\n\n---\n\nThey reached the farm on a warm evening in late May.\n\nSamuel saw it from the top of the last hill—the small house, the barn, the field where his father would be planting corn by now. Smoke rose from the chimney. A cow stood in the pasture, flicking its tail at flies.\n\nHe stopped. Uncle Nate stopped beside him.\n\n\"There it is,\" Uncle Nate said. \"Home.\"\n\nSamuel did not move. He was not sure why. He had thought about this moment for six weeks, imagined walking up the path to the door, seeing his mother's face. But now that it was here, he felt strange. Nervous. Like he was a different person than the boy who had left.\n\n\"Go on,\" Uncle Nate said. \"They're waiting.\"\n\nSamuel walked down the hill.\n\nHis mother saw him first. She came out of the house and stood on the porch, her hand raised to shade her eyes. For a moment she did not move. Then she was running toward him, her skirt flying behind her, and she caught him in her arms and held him tight.\n\n\"You're home,\" she said. \"You're home, you're home.\"\n\nSamuel hugged her back. She smelled like bread and woodsmoke and soap. She smelled like home.\n\nHis father came out of the barn, walking slowly. He stopped a few feet away and looked at Samuel—looked at the calluses on his hands, the sunburn on his face, the way he stood.\n\n\"You made it,\" his father said.\n\n\"Yes, sir.\"\n\n\"Nate says you did good.\"\n\n\"I tried.\"\n\nHis father nodded slowly. Then he held out his hand, the same way he had when Samuel left.\n\nSamuel shook it.\n\n---\n\nThat night, after supper, Samuel sat on the porch and looked at the stars.\n\nThe four silver dollars were in his pocket. He had shown them to his mother, and she had cried. He had given them to his father, who had put them in the tin box under the bed where they kept their savings. Four dollars. Enough for seed, maybe. Enough to help.\n\nBut that was not what Samuel thought about.\n\nHe thought about the river. The sound of water moving under the logs. The weight of the sweep in his hands. The way the current felt when he stood at the edge of the raft and looked south, toward places he had never been.\n\nHe thought about Hendricks, and Peterson, and Garrett with his broken arm. He thought about Captain Rambo, steering them through the rapids. He thought about Uncle Nate's hand on his shoulder after the storm.\n\nHe was home. But part of him was still out there, floating on the brown water, watching the shore slide by.\n\nThe river had changed him. He knew that now. He was not the same boy who had said goodbye to his parents in April. He was someone new. Someone who had done real work, faced real danger, and come through.\n\nNext year, maybe, he would do it again.\n\nBut for now, he was home. And home was good.\n\nSamuel went inside. His mother had made up his bed with clean sheets, and his pillow smelled like lavender from the drawer where she kept it.\n\nHe lay down. He closed his eyes.\n\nAnd he dreamed of the river.\n","narration":null}],"chapterCount":9,"audio":null,"narration":{"hasNarration":false,"chapters":[]},"assets":[],"standalone":false};
